GOLDEN Arrows’ matter is “reaching its final conclusion” for fielding ineligible player Smiso Mbhele. According to the PSL prosecutor Zola Majavu, Arrows have been found not guilty by the league’s Disciplinary Committee (DC) “on how the registration was procured”. But the club was found guilty of the “basis of the registration of the player was improper”. The matter is now in the final stages and the hearing has been scheduled for next Tuesday where the potential sanction will be handed. “I 'm here to provide you a DC matter of Golden Arrows together with their player, Mr Simo Mbhele, who were charged with impropriety pertaining to the registration of Mr Mbhele,” said Majavu. “The matter was fully argued for the DC last week, where after the DC adjourned the proceeding having reserved the ruling, the ruling has now come in and the DC has found as follows: “One, with the regards to the allegations of dishonesty and impropriety pertaining to how the registration of Mr Mbhele was procured, the DC found both Mbhele and Golden Arrows not guilty. “However, the DC found Mr Mbhele and Arrows FC guilty on the basis that the registration of the player itself was improper. “Having been so convicted, the matter now needs to proceed to the final stage, namely that of determining the appropriate sanction. The matter will be enrolled for the hearing on the sanction on the 15th of the February at 5pm, where both parties will be given an opportunity to make their closing submissions. “Once the DC has deliberated and pronounced its sanctions on the ruling, I’ll similarly communicate to everybody.” Arrows are allegedly to have registered Mbhele without an international clearance certificate (ITC) which was supposed to be sent to Arrows by the players previous club 1º Dezembro. 